<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Exporters worry over screwdriver economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING EXPORTERS have warned ministers that the UK will become 'a
screwdriver- assembly economy' if the government's 'lamentable' attitude to
supporting exports is not reversed, the Labour party said yesterday.
A memorandum sent during the general election campaign and leaked to Labour
warns that, without corrective action, the UK's 'only real exports will be
British jobs'. Labour said the memo was backed by organisations, including
the British Exporters' Association. However, its claim that the document was
backed also by the Association of British Chambers of Commerce was denied by
the association last night.
The strong language highlights the private anxieties of many exporters,
particularly since the sale last year of the short-term insurance division
of the government's Export Credits Guarantee Department (ECGD).
It suggests there was an organised lobbying campaign during the election by
exporters to persuade Mr John Major to shake up the Department of Trade and
Industry and put pressure on the Treasury. The memorandum says the
organisations planned 'to convene a press conference in the near future to
expose the fallacy of the Treasury position'.
Yesterday the British Exporters' Association confirmed that it planned to
meet Mr Richard Needham, the new trade minister, on May 26 but refused to
comment on the leaked document. The DTI said the volume of UK exports was at
a record level but that Mr Needham was always ready to listen to industry's
view.
Mr Gordon Brown, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, said that during the
election exporters had met Mr (now Lord) John Wakeham, the former energy
secretary who helped run Conservative Central Office. The prime minister, he
said, had also been involved in discussions.
The memorandum says: 'The Treasury view is that any form of export support
is a subsidy and therefore ideologically unsound. The Treasury would rather
pay unemployment benefit than invest in employment through the promotion of
exports.'
The exporters go on to say that the ECGD sale, plus the introduction of a
Portfolio Management System which introduced stricter disciplines on the
cost of export cover, means 'most small companies do not export because of
lack of incentive or assistance'.
The memorandum concludes: 'On the government's own figures, the balance of
payments will continue to grow in both 1992 and 1993. Unless corrective
action is taken, the UK will become a screwdriver-assembly economy, and our
only real exports will be British jobs.'
</TEXT>
