<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Fifth Heathrow terminal plan: BAA move to beat congestion at
airport welcomed by airline industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAA, the former British Airports Authority, yesterday unveiled its
long-awaited plans to build a Pounds 800m-Pounds 900m fifth terminal at
Heathrow, which handles more international passengers than any other airport
in the world.
The scheme, expected to lead to a lengthy planning inquiry, was attacked by
local residents but welcomed by the airline industry.
Sir John Egan, BAA's chief executive, said the terminal would help Heathrow
maintain its leading international position 'well into the next century' and
safeguard 10,000 jobs there.
It would also provide extra capacity for 30m passengers a year at Heathrow,
one of the world's most congested airports, and a new base for British
Airways, the UK flag carrier which accounts for 40 per cent of Heathrow's
airline traffic.
BAA had originally estimated the cost of building the terminal at Pounds
1.6bn, but Sir John said the estimate had been reduced to Pounds 800m-Pounds
900m because of improved pre-planning and better project management.
The project would be financed from cash flow and some debt, although the
borrowings would not affect the company's current gearing levels, Sir John
said.
Detailed architectural designs have yet to be completed by the Richard
Rogers Partnership. Bovis, the construction arm of the P&amp;O company, is also
working on the project. BAA is hoping to win government approval in 1997
after a public inquiry.
The proposals envisage building the terminal at the west end of the airport
on the site now occupied by the Perry Oaks sludge works. Agreement has been
reached with Thames Water to move the sludge works to the nearby site of an
existing sewage works at Iver South.
The terminal is to be built in two phases. The first would cost about Pounds
500m and be completed in 2002. It would provide capacity for 10m passengers
a year and parking space for 20 aircraft.
The second phase, to be comoverall capacity to 30m passengers a year and
provide parking space for 60 aircraft, including the new generation of very
large widebody airliners.
The terminal will be connected to three satellites linked by underground
'people movers'. Road links and a direct express rail line to central London
are also planned.
Sir John said the project would help Heathrow cope with the increasing
demand for air travel in south-east England. BAA is forecasting a doubling
of annual passenger movements in the London area to 120m passengers by 2002
and a trebling of demand to 170m passengers by 2016.
After the slump in airline traffic caused by the Gulf war and the recession
last year, activity has been steadily improving at BAA's airports.
The company said that last month was its busiest April ever, with BAA
airports handling 6.2m passengers, a 20 per cent increase on April last year
and a 3.6 per cent increase on April 1990.
BAA and the airline industry have long argued for extra capacity at Heathrow
to maintain London's position as the world's leading international passenger
airline hub.
The International Air Transport Association said that, without the new
terminal and other air traffic control and infrastructure investments,
Britain stood to lose Dollars 1bn annually of economic activity by 2000.
But local residents and authorities reacted strongly to the plans, fearing
these would cause even greater noise, traffic congestion and other
disturbances.
In an effort to allay these fears, Sir John said the terminal project did
not involve the construction of a new runway at Heathrow nor extra night
flights because new larger and quieter widebody aircraft would help
transport many more passengers on a single flight.
Flying in the face of local opposition Page 8
</TEXT>
