FT  13 MAY 92 / Network of after-school clubs to be launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is expected next week to announce funding for a national
network of children's after-school clubs and holiday playschemes to be run
through the Training and Enterprise Councils.
The move will be the first to be made by Mrs Gillian Shephard, the
employment secretary, in her role as cabinet minister with responsibility
for women's issues.
The policy will be aimed partly at countering criticism from the Equal
Opportunities Commission and other groups that the government has failed to
provide an overall childcare strategy and that out-of-school provision
remains patchy and inadequate.
The idea of funding the initiative through the 82 employer-led Tecs would be
to draw in private sector finance. Most employers would find it impractical
to run schemes themselves but may want to buy places in local after-school
clubs and holiday playschemes.
About 20 per cent of children of primary-school age are estimated to be
'latchkey' children, according to Kids Clubs Network, the voluntary group
which campaigns for after-school provision.
Ms Tess Woodcraft, Kids Clubs Network director, said there were between 400
and 500 after-school clubs in the UK, mostly run by parents on 'very tiny
grants'.
