<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 92 / Deal sets up trade in pollution permits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE first US deal to trade pollution rights was announced yesterday when the
federally-owned Tennessee Valley Authority said it had agreed to purchase
allowances to emit 10,000 tons of sulphur dioxide, a key cause of acid rain,
from privately owned Wisconsin Power &amp; Light.
The terms of the sale were not disclosed, but the estimated cost is Dollars
2.5m to Dollars 3m (Pounds 1.4m to Pounds 1.7m).
To help ease the high costs of converting to cleaner technologies, the US
government has created a system under which 'dirtier' utility companies can
buy allowances for emissions from 'cleaner' companies that have exceeded the
federal standards.
The deal is, in essence, a forward contract on the allowances that will be
issued next year by the Environmental Protection Agency under the terms of
the 1990 Clean Air Act. The act requires that utility companies cut their
sulphur dioxide emissions in half by 2000, or from a national total of 19m
tons to 9m tons. The first deadline for partial compliance is 1995.
The allowances have been allocated, but will not be in the hands of
utilities until an auction in March 1993.
Mr Erroll Davis, president of Wisconsin Power &amp; Light, said the transaction
'clearly demonstrates that a market-based approach can be an effective way
to address environmental problems'.
There has, however, been scepticism over how well such a market can work, as
state and locally-controlled utilities have been slow to set any clear
policies for trading allowances. There are also doubts over whether a given
community would want to be 'dirty' even at a lower cost, and over how to
price the allowances.
The Chicago Board of Trade, the world's largest futures market, plans to
begin trading futures contracts on the allowances, dubbed pollution futures.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8547</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEMBDAAVFT</PROFILE>
