<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / International Capital Markets: Reduction in new bank lending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE international financial system generated Dollars 255bn of new lending
last year, less than half of the Dollars 550bn of 1990, according to figures
published in the BIS quarterly review, writes Richard Waters.
The scarcity of new bank credit was at the root of the contraction, net
international lending by banks plummeting from Dollars 465bn to Dollars
85bn. Despite this, the final quarter of last year saw a slight recovery in
bank lending. New lending in the last quarter, at Dollars 30bn, was double
the previous quarter's.
Japanese banks accounted for much of this growth. They put on Dollars 23bn
of new international assets, most of it to fund the affiliates of Japanese
companies in other Asian centres. Japanese banks also continued to reduce
their dependence on foreign finance.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
