<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / International Company News: Earnings dive at Turner
Broadcasting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COSTS associated with coverage of the winter Olympics contributed to a sharp
decline in first-quarter net earnings at Turner Broadcasting System, the
media and entertainment group that controls the CNN cable network.
Although revenues were 12 per cent higher at Dollars 365.2m, the
first-quarter net profit was only Dollars 731,000 , against Dollars 3.8m a
year ago.
At the operating level the profit dropped by 9 per cent to Dollars 51.1m.
Revenues for the entertainment division of Mr Ted Turner's company rose by
20 per cent to Dollars 170.5m thanks to increases in subscription revenue
and advertising at the TNT cable network. But the entertainment unit's
operating profit fell to Dollars 16.1m from Dollars 27.9m in the first
quarter of last year.
Operating profits from the news division - which includes CNN - increased to
Dollars 42.4m from Dollars 31.1m on revenues that were 9 per cent higher at
Dollars 125.3m.
Losses on the sports division, which includes an equity stake in the Atlanta
Hawks basketball team, rose to nearly Dollars 4m from Dollars 2.1m a year
ago.
The New York Times, whose delivery drivers have been on strike since last
week, said yesterday the strike had cost millions of dollars. Mr Lance
Primis, president of the paper, said the losses consisted of plant and
equipment damage, lost sales and rebates to advertisers.
Mr Primis said he was unaware of distribution problems spreading beyond the
suburban areas of Westchester County and Long Island in New York and in
Connecticut.
