<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / International Company News: Wasserstein settles Interco suit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WASSERSTEIN Perella, the investment banking business set up by two prominent
Wall Street bid advisers in 1988, has agreed to pay Dollars 18.25m to
Interco in settlement of a legal action brought against it by the St
Louis-based furniture and shoe manufacturer.
Wasserstein maintains that it has no liability to Interco, to whom it gave
investment banking advice in the late 1980s. It said that the settlement
'reflects growing concerns as to the unpredictability of the outcome of jury
trials, regardless of the merits of the case'.
Nevertheless, the payment will be seen as a further blow to the investment
banking firm, which has been losing ground in the bid-advisory league tables
in recent years.
Wasserstein was formed by Mr Joseph Perella and Mr Bruce Wasserstein, two
high fliers previously with First Boston. It ranked third in the merger and
acquisition league tables in 1989, according to Securities Data. It had
slipped to 12th place last year, and came 15th in the first quarter of 1992.
Interco had brought legal action against Wasserstein as a result of advice
received at the end of the 1980s. The company 'recapitalised' in 1988 in an
attempt to avoid a hostile takeover. This involved Interco taking on a large
amount of debt and paying special dividends to shareholders.
The company subsequently sought protection under Chapter 11 of the US
Bankruptcy Code after asset sales failed to generate as much money as
projected and earnings fell short of forecasts.
Interco sued its former investment banker, Wasserstein Perella, in January
1991, claiming that Wasserstein had delayed the sale of its Ethan Allen
subsidiary, and caused it to accept a lower price. The Interco suit had
originally asked for Dollars 109m, plus punitive damages.
In March last year, an 'examiner' - a bankruptcy and creditors' rights
lawyer - was asked by the bankruptcy court to consider whether the
recapitalisation gave rise to possible legal claims by the company and
creditors against former professional advisers.
In her report, the examiner concluded that the Dollars 2.8bn
recapitalisation did render Interco insolvent, and that there had,
therefore, been a fraudulent conveyance of assets. However, she spread the
blame widely, effectively exonerating Wasserstein on the grounds that
company officials has misled it.
'They (Wasserstein) performed their services at a level that was acceptable
by investment banking industry standards,' she said. The examiner added that
'their real problem was that they were not given complete information from
the company'.
However, her report did not address the Ethan Allen issue in any detail.
No claims were subsequently brought against Wasserstein Perella over the
recapitalisation itself.
The Ethan Allen suit was complex, but essentially it alleged that
Wasserstein 'failed and refused' to execute a fairness opinion which would
have allowed a proposed sale of the subsidiary in 1988 for Dollars 475m to
go ahead. The business was eventually sold for Dollars 385.5m in 1989.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
