<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Kohl plea for German wage restraint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR HELMUT KOHL, the German chancellor, yesterday rejected any attempt to
link new private sector pay deals to last week's public sector award of 5.4
per cent, and called for restraint in wage claims and public spending.
In an urgent appeal to employers and trade unions, he threw his weight
behind the austerity programme of Mr Theo Waigel, finance minister,
promising savings across the board in the federal budget, but no tax
increases.
At the same time, he warned that the rapidly rising wages in east Germany
were undermining private investment flows and preventing the gradual
equalisation of living standards between the two halves of the country.
His appeal was launched at a combined meeting of employers, trade unions and
the leaders of the 16 German states to discuss the continuing plight of the
east German economy and the financial pressures on both public and private
sectors.
It comes at a moment when further strikes are threatened in the engineering
and construction industries, as well as by print workers, in the wake of
last week's pay deal for almost 3m public sector workers.
It also coincides with crumbling popularity for his ruling coalition and
widespread scepticism about the promised austerity programme in the light of
the public sector award.
'This agreement was a very hard decision for us to take,' Mr Kohl said.
'Both for the whole economy and for public spending it contains incalculable
risks.'
Yet the government was forced to go 'beyond the limit' because of an
arbitration award of 5.4 per cent, which aroused 'exaggerated expectations'.
Mr Kohl also blamed unnamed state premiers and city mayors, who 'stabbed the
negotiators in the back' by recommending a deal at the last moment. He
rejected any attempt to link the deal with the private sector pay talks
under way.
'There can be no pay leadership of the public service for the private
sector,' he said. 'Every sector must reach a wage agreement which is
bearable in relation both to the challenges of German unity and growing
international competition.'
He warned that east Germany was falling behind, with private sector
investment per capita running at only two-thirds of the level in west
Germany. Wages and salaries had reached 44 per cent of the western level in
1991, while productivity was only 29 per cent.
The chancellor's appeal was met by stern resistance from the DGB, the trade
union federation, whose leader, Mr Heinz-Werner Meyer, rejected any plea for
a 'change of course' in wage talks. He also warned against any attempt to
put the brunt of public sector spending cuts on programmes for retraining
and cushioning the impact of eastern unemployment.
The one positive sign for Mr Kohl yesterday was the agreement by the
opposition Social Democrats (SPD) to take part in cross-party talks on the
growing economic crisis on May 27.
The federal budget this year is likely to have a net borrowing requirement
of DM45bn (Pounds 15.3bn), and there is widespread scepticism that the
government can reduce that to the planned DM25bn by 1995 without
supplementary taxes, or without drastic cuts in social spending - both still
ruled out by Mr Kohl.
German trade surplus soars to DM 4.9bn
</TEXT>
