FT  12 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour left demands full debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leftwingers are set to exploit the vacuum left by the leadership
election by demanding more freedom to express their differences with the
front bench when MPs meet for the first full parliamentary party meeting
tomorrow.
The growing pressure for a right to express constructive dissent follows
from a widely held belief that Mr Neil Kinnock's regime was too tough in
silencing party loyalists who differed on policy issues.
Members of the 100-strong Tribune group, once designated leftwing but widely
seen as a support group for Mr Kinnock in the final years of his leadership,
are also expected to re-establish their independence. Moves are afoot to
introduce a new rule that would preclude frontbench members from holding
office.
The Campaign Group, depleted in recent years to about 20 members, is also
expecting some recruits from the 60-odd new MPs.
Party leaders are expected to face some criticism at tomorrow's
parliamentary party meeting on the conduct of the general election campaign.
