FT  12 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory Euro-sceptics threaten
rebellion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY 'Euro-sceptics' say more than a dozen Conservative MPs are prepared to
vote against the government over the legislation ratifying the Maastricht
agreement. Such a move might put the government's majority at risk.
The Euro-sceptics believe that the debate on the European Community has
moved on since just a handful of Tories voted against the Maastricht deal
when MPs debated it last December, and point to the much greater prospect of
putting the government under pressure than when it had a majority of more
than 80 before the election.
They say that now that MPs are not under pressure to show pre-election
loyalty, some colleagues who abstained then will vote against the government
this time.
The MPs are discussing tactics and organising themselves in preparation for
the first debate on the bill, which is due to come before the Commons next
week. The committed will now try to persuade colleagues who have expressed
some concern about the agreement.
Leading campaigners are said to include former energy minister Mr Michael
Spicer (Worcestershire South), Mr James Cran (Beverley) and Mr Christopher
Gill (Ludlow).
Although no one has been excluded, the campaigners have little hope that
many of the new Tory MPs will join the rebellion, because they recognise how
hard it is for newcomers to defy the whips so soon after arriving at
Westminster.
One new Tory said he would probably vote for the government reluctantly and
would make his unease known to the whips.
The Labour party has not yet agreed how it is likely to vote on the bill.
One likely course is to put down and vote for an amendment in favour of the
social chapter, from which the UK 'opted out', but the party might abstain
on the bill itself.
The Euro-sceptics emphasise that although the government may get its
majority on the bill, Europe will remain a controversial issue.
The Tory MPs who voted against the Maastricht deal last December included
former leader of the Commons Mr John Biffen (Shropshire North); Mr Nicholas
Budgen (Wolverhampton South West); Mr Richard Shepherd (Aldridge-Brownhills)
and Mr Bill Walker (Tayside North).
Mr Ian Lang last night dampened expectations of imminent moves towards
constitutional reform for Scotland, saying that the Scottish Conservatives
had fought the recent general election 'above all else as a unionist party.'
The government remained willing to 'consider' ways of improving present
mechanisms, as long as they did not 'jeopardise' the integrity of the UK, Mr
Lang said.
</TEXT>
