FT  12 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Pressure for action on Maxwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS ARE to come under fresh pressure over the plight of pensioners of
companies formerly owned by Robert Maxwell, after an informal cross-party
meeting of MPs this afternoon.
Mr Richard Page, Tory MP for Hertfordshire South-West and one of the
organisers of the meeting, said yesterday that the government should give an
up-to-date statement or provide time for a Commons debate, because in
certain cases the pension money would run out at the end of June.
He also expected the meeting to agree to put a firm request to ministers for
an investigation into the role of the Investment Management Regulatory
Organisation (Imro), the self-regulatory body for the fund management
industry, which has come in for particular criticism.
The MPs are likely to renew questions to Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the
governor of the Bank of England, calling on the Bank to take a more active
approach to its supervisory role.
The meeting may also lead to pressure for the early re-establishment of the
cross-party social security committee, so it can continue its investigation
into the affair. Mr Frank Field, the Labour chairman of the committee in the
last parliament, is the meeting's co-sponsor.
So far since the election, the government's only comment on the Maxwell
affair has come from Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary. Last
Thursday he rejected opposition calls for the government to commit itself to
underwriting any shortfall in Maxwell pension funds, but promised to
announce plans to review the framework of occupational pension law in the
next few weeks.
In the Commons, delays over the mounting of prosecutions in cases where
former employees of companies controlled by Maxwell had been 'swindled' out
of their pension rights were criticised by Mr David Winnick (Lab Walsall
North).
He pressed for an assurance that there would be no 'cover-up' over what had
occured in Maxwell's companies.
The attorney general, Sir Nicholas Lyell, said the matters arising from the
Maxwell case were being carefully, professionally and expeditiously
investigated by a special team.
Referring to a meeting of the Commons social security committee in January,
Mr David Harris (C St Ives) recalled that counsel representing one of Mr
Maxwell's sons said he should not answer questions because 'he believed he
was on the threshold of charges'.
Sir Nicholas emphasised that the counsel who appeared before the select
committee for Mr Maxwell had no authority to speak one way or the other for
the prosecution.
Also yesterday, Mr Dennis Skinner (Lab Bolsover), called for a fraud squad
investigation into Olympia and York, the troubled property developer
involved in Europe's biggest new office project at Canary Wharf in London.
He said it was a 'scandal' that the company, which owed Dollars 12bn (Pounds
6.7bn), was now in hock to the banks which, as in the Maxwell case, were
having to 'loan it money in order to keep it afloat'. Mr Skinner also said
it was 'despicable' that the government was bailing out the company.
Resolution nears, Page 22
</TEXT>
