<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Ashdown seeks the right chord - The
debate over the future of the Liberal Democrats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, thought the world would have
changed when he arrived at the Commons yesterday, then indefatigable
optimism had got the better of him.
His weekend speech calling for Labour to work with him on an anti-Tory
alliance opened up age-old questions among Liberal Democrat MPs about the
role of the third party in a inherently two-party system.
There is no sign that the answers are any clearer.
His well-timed comments were strong on mood music but devoid of
prescription. The text suggested he believes in more than Micawberism -
waiting for something to turn up - and is restless about leading a party
with a voice only in local government and think tanks. But his vision lacked
a specific end game - even if Labour were to play ball.
It was probably quite enough for his parliamentary colleagues at this stage,
however. They are too used to misplaced promises of late surges or of
promised breakthroughs that became mirages. The consensus among the party's
MPs was that change had to be gradual.
Mr Charles Kennedy, party president, said: 'I don't think realistically that
we are going to see anything happen on the centre left until Labour have got
themselves sorted out, probably not until next spring.' Even then there
would be no scope for 'compromising our intellectual integrity'.
Liberal Democrat MPs see their general election performance only as a
success - even though the party's share of the vote fell 5 points and
parliamentary representation shrank by 2.
The result is a rather grandiloquent presumption, which Mr Ashdown seems
anxious to rework that the impossible might still be achievable without a
fundamental rethink of strategy.
Mr Simon Hughes, Liberal Democrat MP for Southwark and Bermondsey, said:
'There is a fairly widespread view that our job is to keep our identity,
avoid getting into pact/deal muddles and achieve the end of Tory rule
without allowing Labour to recover. It is how you do that which is
difficult.'
He encapsulated the party's internal contradictions, however, by adding:
'For most Liberal Democrat members and MPs, there is a limit to the number
of times you can see your party return to be a third party and in
opposition.'
Freshly elected MPs such as Mr Don Foster, who defeated former Tory chairman
Mr Chris Patten in Bath, are keen for influence on the issues that won them
their seats - education, unemployment and so on. But Mr Foster, too, insists
that that has to be 'subject to being totally unwilling to give up the
philosophy of the party'.
Given that sense of wanting to have their cake and eat it, coupled with
Liberal Democrat MPs' determination neither to bend too far towards either
Labour or the Tories, Mr Ashdown was careful in his speech to set out how
Labour would have to move towards him. He would, after all, risk losing his
own Yeovil constituency if he were to let an unreconstructed Labour party
into office.
So Labour needs to back liberal market economics, not producer interests;
embrace constitutional reform; oppose authoritarian and remote government;
and break links with the trade unions, for Mr Ashdown's support.
Since the election, though, his thinking has moved away from aiming to
replace Labour as the main opposition party. His failure to win electoral
reform notwithstanding, he now wants to move towards a European-style
pluralism with opposition political parties competing and co-operating. He
knows he cannot both set out to destroy the Labour party and urge its
friendship.
Yet his careful balancing means that even Labour MPs who would be willing to
start a dialogue are deeply distrustful. One shadow cabinet member said
yesterday Mr Ashdown was too arrogant. 'A bit of humility would be nice.'
Mr Ashdown talks of the Liberal Democrats' acting as a catalyst or 'the
gathering point for a broader movement'. In practice, he may be content to
move his party towards some form of consensus-building forum with an agenda
initiated by the new Labour leadership.
Conceivably, some of his colleagues might be prepared to compromise their
ambitions a little if, for instance, Labour were to become committed to
electoral reform.
Mr Hughes said: 'All of us are willing to facilitate ways of bringing about
an end to minority Tory government. That means exploring ways of creating a
coalition of parties and individuals committed to electoral and
constitutional reform.'
Mr Ashdown has wisely refused so far to enter into speculation about what
might or might not be workable. In reality, at this stage he does not know;
and he is aware of the sensitivities of excessive risk-taking that might
scare some Liberal Democrat MPs, perhaps too used to the tranquil waters of
third party politics.
His quest for real Liberal Democrat influence means, however, that he is
unlikely to be restrained for long.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
