<PROFILE>_AN-CELA7AFLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920512
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Waldegrave pledge on openness in
government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT will publish the membership of cabinet committees, which make
many important decisions, within the next few days, Mr William Waldegrave
said yesterday.
He also pledged the publication of the 'guidance for ministers', rules which
prevent conflicts between ministers' private interests and public
responsibilities.
Opening the fourth day's debate on the Queen's Speech, the Citizen's Charter
minister denounced the 'disastrous attempt to make the state the production
manager' of services and industries.
The initiatives follow a general election undertaking by Mr John Major, the
prime minister, to promote more open government. There should be far more
openness 'from Whitehall to the local school', Mr Waldegrave said.
To a cacophony of protests and interventions from the Labour left wing, Mr
Waldegrave devoted the bulk of his address to outlining the shortcomings of
state ownership of industry and public services.
Nationalisation had been damaging both for the industries concerned and
consumers, he said. It was 'the central initiative' of Mr Major's
administration to return government to its 'proper role' and the remaining
nationalised industries to the marketplace.
The philosophy was not shared by all Conservatives present, however. Mr
Robert Adley, the Tory MP for Christchurch, cautioned against the automatic
assumption that the state has no role to play in any of the leading
industries or services. 'We don't want Wessex fighting Mercia in privatised
armies,' he said.
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary and a contender for the Labour
party's deputy leadership, called for 'stupid' Treasury rules limiting
public-sector access to private finance to be changed.
Ms Glenda Jackson (Lab Hampstead and Highgate), one of several MPs to make
maiden speeches during yesterday's debate, said Britain should do more for
the Third World, targeting aid on the poorest countries and on the basic
requirements of health care.
See Observer
</TEXT>
