FT  12 MAY 92 / BCCI creditors win further adjournment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HIGH COURT granted a further adjournment yesterday to creditors of the
failed Bank of Credit and Commerce International who last week decided to
reject the proposed liquidation settlement negotiated with the Abu Dhabi
majority shareholders.
During a brief hearing lawyers for the creditors said they were seeking
clarification on the deal from the majority shareholders.
The British-based creditors are unhappy with the terms of the deal but
officials involved in the negotiations believe there is little room for
manoeuvre within the Pounds 1.7bn compensation package al-ready agreed with
Abu Dhabi.
Mr Brian Smouha, the Touche Ross chief liquidator who negotiated the deal,
refused to comment on the impasse yesterday.
The hearing will reconvene on June 8, when the liquidator will be anxious to
have secured creditors' approval as the timetable for the deal assumes that
court approvals for the deal will have been obtained by June 30.
Before the provisions in the draft agreement can take effect, the
liquidators must also secure acceptance of creditors with claims totalling
Dollars 7bn (Pounds 3.9bn) by September 30.
Outside court, Mr Keith Vaz, Labour MP for Leicester East, who has
campaigned for a better deal for depositors and former bank staff, urged Mr
Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, to intervene on behalf of depositors.
The Foreign Office said yesterday that no intervention was planned.
