FT  12 MAY 92 / Price Waterhouse faces renewed action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRICE WATERHOUSE, the accountancy firm, faces the prospect of renewed legal
action over its role as auditor to BCCI after demands from plaintiffs in a
US precedent-setting lawsuit to re-try its case.
Milberg Weiss, the law firm bringing the suit against 77 defendants
including PW, lodged a document with the California central district court
yesterday requesting 'vacation' of a ruling at the end of last month that
its case should be dismissed.
Judge Consuelo Marshall dismissed the case - believed to have cost PW more
than Dollars 250,000 (Pounds 140,000) a month in legal fees - on April 30.
That left the plaintiffs the option of appealing to a higher court.
Milberg Weiss alleged yesterday that there was a conflict of interest by two
of Judge Marshall's law clerks. It claimed that they had worked on the BCCI
lawsuit after accepting employment from law firms representing key
defendants in other BCCI actions. It says it initially notified the court of
its concerns after Judge Marshall's preliminary ruling on the case at the
end of March.
The documents say the class action suit is being brought by a handful of
plaintiffs on behalf of approximately 800,000 depositors who have lost in
aggregate Dollars 8bn-Dollars 10bn.
