<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Ryan Group will bid in coal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RYAN GROUP, the UK's largest privately owned coal producer, said yesterday
that it would bid for part of British Coal when it is privatised.
The company's announcement that it had restructured its finances in
preparation for a possible bid was the first sign of potential buyers
gathering as the government pushes ahead its plans to sell British Coal.
Ryan has received a Pounds 50m equity injection from a City consortium led
by Electra, the fund management company. That will strengthen Ryan's capital
base so that it can take advantage of any opportunities to buy parts of
British Coal. Electra, together with consortium partners Bankers Trust and
Creditanstalt, will also provide a Pounds 65m loan facility, of which Pounds
35m will be used initially.
Mr Crispian Hotson, Ryan's chief executive, said that mining companies such
as Anglo-United, Hanson, and RTZ, as well as international coal companies,
would bid for parts of British Coal.
Ryan will be one of the smallest companies interested in British Coal - it
produces 6m tonnes of coal compared with British Coal's 90m. Mr Hotson threw
down a challenge to British Coal. 'We could get their costs down, and so
could a number of international companies,' he said.
He rejected reports from NM Rothschild, the merchant bank advising on the
privatisation, forecasting that competition from gas and imported coal might
force British Coal's total output down from 90m tonnes to 35m - 40m tonnes.
British Coal's pits could produce 50m tonnes of competitive coal, he said.
At world prices, that might mean a revenue of close to Pounds 1bn.
Although there are so far no details of how British Coal might be sold, it
is likely that it will be split into several companies, and Ryan hopes it
will be able to bid for smaller businesses. Although Ryan did not indicate
how much it might spend, it is likely to be interested in south Wales, where
it has some deep mines, or the profitable opencast mining business, where it
works as a contractor to British Coal.
'We aren't interested in huge tonnages,' Mr Hotson said. 'We want the bit
you can make money out of.'
The Electra deal will enable Ryan to clear the debt of more than Pounds 100m
it inherited from the management buy-out that formed the company from the
quoted company Ryan International in 1989. In the year ending December 1990
(the last published results) the company's interest charge of close to
Pounds 20m cancelled out its Pounds 11.2m operating profit.
</TEXT>
