FT  12 MAY 92 / Demand for credit weakens in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMAND for credit by consumers was weak in the first quarter, according to
government figures released yesterday which did little to support theories
about economic upturn before the general election.
According to the Central Statistical Office, consumers repaid a net Pounds
270m on credit agreements between January and March, the largest quarterly
repayment since records began in 1975.
In the final quarter of last year there was a seasonally adjusted repayment
of a revised Pounds 16m, while in the previous quarter net new borrowing
came to Pounds 234m.
The period between October last year and March marks the first time since
1975 in which consumers have made net repayments on this type of credit for
two consecutive quarters.
The figures underline the weakness in the economy that was behind the
government's decision last week to reduce interest rates by 0.5 of a point
to 10 per cent.
The Conservatives' election victory, however, may have provoked a spurt in
economic activity that has yet to show up in statistics.
Yesterday's figures apply to virtually all forms of consumer credit except
mortgages. On March 31, Pounds 52.8bn was outstanding on such credit,
compared with Pounds 53.07bn at the end of last year.
In the first quarter, consumers repaid loans on bank personal accounts worth
Pounds 249m, the first quarter since records started to have shown a
repayment. Between October and December last year, net new loans on personal
accounts came to Pounds 100m.
Net new borrowings in the first quarter on credit cards came to Pounds 125m,
little changed from the Pounds 133m registered in the final three months of
last year.
A breakdown of the data shows that in March consumers repaid Pounds 69m on
the so-called narrow measure of credit - which accounts for about 60 per
cent of all credit and fails to include bank loans on personal accounts, and
loans on credit cards outside the Mastercard and Visa systems. It also
excludes loans from insurance companies and retailers.
The March figure means that in seven out of the past eight months consumers
have made a repayment on this measure of credit, which includes non-mortgage
loans with building societies and finance houses.
See Lex
</TEXT>
