<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Israel's hopes for closer EC ties fade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community told Israel last night that its prospects for closer
economic ties with the Twelve were dim until Israel proved more conciliatory
in the Middle East peace talks and more appreciative of the EC's role in the
peace process.
Israel objects to full EC participation in the talks on disarmament. The
atmosphere for last night's meeting of the EC-Israel Co-operation Council
was further soured by Israel's boycott of a parallel meeting in Brussels of
the peace conference's working group on regional economic development,
chaired by the EC.
Mr David Levy, Israel's foreign minister, repeated his government's
objection to meeting, in this group, Palestinians from outside the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
Mr Joao de Deus Pinheiro, Portugal's foreign minister, said he hoped that at
least Israel would attend future sessions of this working group.
For his part, Mr Levy expressed dismay that the Community had recently
pressurised its neighbours in the European Free Trade Association (Efta)
into refusing to sign a free trade accord with Israel. EC leverage on Efta
is considerable, because many Efta members have applied for full EC
membership.
Israel has been pushing for its trade and financial agreement with the EC to
be updated and expanded, particularly in the light of the commercial
concessions Brussels is granting to the countries of Efta and central
Europe.
</TEXT>
