<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Picking president proves tough task for Italy's political
parties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WITH tomorrow's presidential election looming, Italy's political parties
yesterday intensified their efforts to agree on a candidate.
Since Mr Francesco Cossiga resigned as the country's eighth president on
April 25, the main parties have been torn by internal divisions and doubts
about the type of person who should become head of state when the two houses
of parliament, plus 58 delegates from regional councils, meet to vote
tomorrow.
The politicians are having to take account of the profound public
disaffection with the Italian political system and demands for serious
institutional reform evidenced by the vote in the April 5 general election.
This has made it difficult for the outgoing coalition of Christian
Democrats, Socialists, Social Democrats and Liberals to push through their
own candidate without a broader consensus.
The Christian Democrats, as the largest parliamentary party and with a
strong claim to the presidency, have come under pressure to make the first
move. However, they have been shaken by the general election when their vote
fell below 30 per cent for the first time.
Much of the blame has fallen on the the party's two heavy-weight contenders
 -Mr Giulio Andreotti, the outgoing premier, and Mr Arnaldo Forlani, the
party secretary. Before the general election, Mr Andreotti had made it clear
the presidency was the last great office he had not held and his candidacy
would be a fitting conclusion to more than 40 years in politics.
The Socialists for their part have been badly tainted by the municipal
corruption scandal in Milan, the power base of the party leader, Mr Bettino
Craxi.
Last night, the city's mayor, Mr Piero Borghini, announced his resignation
after the muncipal council had become unworkable as a result of the
political impact of the affair in which the Socialists are allegedly heavily
involved in the channeling of funds from rigged contracts to political
parties.
The broad-based council administration automatically resigned with him and
last night it was unclear how the city would find durable government without
fresh elections. Mr Borghini, a former editor of the Communist daily,
L'Unita and left-wing independent, agreed to take-over as mayor barely 100
days ago.
The city's two previous mayors are currently being investigated by
magistrates for alleged corruption. But there has been no suggestion of Mr
Borghini's involvement in the affair, which has lead to 26 local
politicians, businessmen and officials being arrested.
The scandal has damaged Mr Craxi, and although he has mainly had his eye on
the next premiership, he has been a presidential possible.
However, in what appeared to be an acknowledgement that he was out of the
running, Mr Craxi last night nominted Mr Giuliano Vassalli, a former
Socialist justice minister and current member of the constitutional court,
to be the party's candidate.
Whatever deal is cut on the presidency, it is likely to be part of a broader
arrangement over the formation of a new government. Since the president's
powers are largely formal, involving the dissolution of parliament and
nomination of prime ministers, the main parties may be willing to let a
lesser figure or someone from a minor party hold the office.
There are three other Christian Democrat possibilities: Mr Ciriaco de Mita,
party president and former prime minister; Mr Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, recently
elected leader of the Chamber of Deputies; and Ms Tina Anselmi, a veteran
parliamentarian with substantial cross-party support.
Mr Giovanni Spadolini, the Republic's interim president, must stand a good
chance. As a former prime minister he is a skilful political consensus
builder and has a good public image as an amiable father-figure.
The Party of the Democratic Left (former Communist party) is proposing Ms
Nilde Iotti, for 11 years leader of the Chamber of Deputies.
Of the outsiders, the best known is octogenarian left-wing philosopher
Norberto Bobbio. But Mr Cossiga is also on the side-lines ready to be
recalled.
In the first three votes a two-thirds majority is necessary; thereafter a
simple majority. On previous occasions such has been the disagreement that
the voting has gone to 23 sessions.
This time the individual votes of politicians in 16 different parties will
have to be taken into account by the lobbyists.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
