<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / UK wins sympathy but little support on frontier checks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN yesterday won some sympathy from its European Community partners on
the political sensitivity of immigration, but got little support for its
refusal to stop checks on non-EC citizens entering the UK from elsewhere in
the Community after this year.
The controversial issue was discussed by EC foreign ministers, meeting in
Brussels. The discussion, however, did nothing to close the rift over the
issue.
The EC Commission and most EC states want all controls on travel within the
Community to end next year, whereas Britain contends that free travel rights
apply only to EC citizens. Controlling non-EC citizens requires,
necessarily, some checks on EC citizens.
Only Ireland, which effectively has a passport union with the UK, yesterday
expressed some oblique support for Britain's position.
Dublin is worried that, if it follows the EC majority in dropping intra-EC
controls while the UK does not, a new barrier will be erected between the UK
and Ireland.
Mr Douglas Hurd, Britain's foreign secretary, said London's difference with
its EC partners was long-standing and rooted in geography.
As an island nation, 'there are possibilities open to us to control
movements at airports and seaports which are not open to others', he said.
The UK has agreed to sign a convention strengthening the EC's external
frontier, at present stymied by a dispute with Spain over how it would
affect Gibraltar. But UK ministers say it might be years before such an
external control gave the UK the confidence to abandon checks on passengers
arriving from other points in the EC.
</TEXT>
