<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Unions urge OECD to act on unemployed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE UNIONS in the world's leading industrialised countries have called on
governments to implement 'active structural policies' with a strong focus on
infrastructure investment to combat a sharp rise in unemployment.
Responding to a 5m increase in the jobless in the industrialised world over
the past two years, the trade union advisory committee of the 24-nation
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development said governments
should agree a range of policies to reduce unemployment at the next week's
OECD ministerial meeting in Paris and July's Group of Seven summit in
Munich.
It said the OECD should specify a programme of 'vigorous government action'
to deal with the problem. This should include more investment in
infrastructure, investment,assistance for local and regional development
spending, and policies to raise the purchasing power of the poor.
In recent years, the OECD ministerial meeting has tended to listen to and
then ignore the committee's views. Ministers are unlikely to accept the need
for more state spending to combat joblessness. Instead, they are expected to
promote 'active' labour market policies that shift the emphasis to
incentives for the unemployed to seek jobs.
</TEXT>
