<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Exchange tightens ruleson directors' share deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIGHTER RULES on share dealings by directors of listed companies, and on
dealings by their families and associates, were issued yesterday by the
London Stock Exchange after the share-rigging scandal surrounding the late
Robert Maxwell.
Had they been in force before, the rules would have prevented Maxwell and
Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank, from agreeing an options deal which
has subsequently been the subject of intense scrutiny by various regulatory
bodies. The deal gave Goldman the right to sell 15.6m shares in Maxwell
Communication Corporation (MCC) to Maxwell at a pre-agreed price.
The exchange did not name Maxwell or MCC when issuing the rules. However,
the changes are believed to have been provoked entirely by revelations about
dealings in MCC shares and options on MCC shares between the summer of 1990
and Maxwell's death last autumn.
The rules, to take effect on June 1, will force directors to disclose share
dealings by people, companies or other entities to which they are connected.
Previously only dealings by directors and their immediate families needed to
be disclosed.
The definition of 'connected' parties includes trusts in which directors or
their families have an interest. It also extends to associated companies -
those in which directors have at least a 20 per cent stake. The Stock
Exchange has taken the definition of 'connected' from section 346 of the
1985 Companies Act. This embraces, for instance, dealings by a director's
illegitimate children, though not by any children who are over 18.
In addition, dealings in options on a company's shares are to be brought
within the disclosure requirements for the first time. The new rules are
linked to the exchange's model code of dealings by directors, which forbids
directors to deal in the period before a results announcement.
Such a rule could have prevented Maxwell from selling a controversial 'put'
option over MCC shares to Goldman Sachs in August 1990, during the 'closed'
period ahead of a results announcement. The option, giving Goldman the right
to sell MCC shares to Maxwell at a predetermined price in effect put a floor
under the MCC share price during the autumn of 1990.
The exchange's new rules will not have the force of law, but breaches will
give the market authorities the power to suspend trading in a company's
shares or delist it altogether.
MPs pressed on pensions, Page 12
Maxwell's life insurance, Page 22
</TEXT>
