<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Quarter of British Rail routes fail timetable targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A QUARTER of all rail routes in Britain are failing to meet punctuality
targets set under the British Rail Passenger's Charter. Users of the worst
lines, however, will not qualify for compensation unless the poor
performance continues until the end of the year.
Figures published by BR yesterday are the first to show its performance
against targets on a line-by-line basis since the Passenger's Charter was
launched two months ago.
The worst route for punctuality has been Network SouthEast's London-Kent
coast line, on which only 73.2 per cent of peak-hour trains reached their
destination less than five minutes late. The target for the line is 83.3 per
cent.
For cancellations, equal worst are Network SouthEast's London-Tilbury and
Southend line and Regional Railways' north-east lines, both of which ran
96.6 per cent of scheduled trains. The target throughout BR is 99 per cent.
One surprise is the particularly poor performance of the InterCity sector,
customarily portrayed by BR as the jewel in its crown. All but two of
InterCity's seven routes fell short of punctuality targets, some widely. Of
the two lines that did pass the punctuality test, one - the Gatwick Express
 -failed on reliability.
The best line in Britain appears to be Regional Railways' North Wales line,
which scored 98.2 per cent on punctuality and 99.7 per cent on reliability.
InterCity's best performer is the Great Western route from London
Paddington. Network SouthEast's leader is London Euston-Northampton.
Under the charter, regular rail users will receive discounts on season
ticket renewals if their lines fail to meet performance targets by more than
a narrow margin over a 12-month period. However, monitoring began only in
January, so BR can avoid discounts if it brings performance up to par by
year end.
BR said yesterday that although 11 of its 44 routes had failed to meet
punctuality targets, only seven of the lines were performing badly enough to
trigger discounts if they failed to improve.
Chart and details, Page 8
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
