<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Queen drawn into Tory wrangle over Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE QUEEN was last night embroiled in the Conservative party's internal
wrangling over Britain's future in Europe as she prepared to deliver her
first ever address to the European Parliament in Strasbourg today.
A draft speech, reflecting a more positive UK approach to the Community, was
the focus of controversy as Buckingham Palace and Downing Street struggled
to maintain the monarch's aloofness from the party political fray.
In the original draft, the Queen was understood to dismiss differences in
national parliamentary traditions as 'insignificant' when set against the
European commitment to reconciliation and democracy. Her text was also said
to commend the European Parliament for playing 'an ever more important part'
in building common interests between the EC nations.
However, last night it looked likely that the final wording of the speech
will be altered to avoid offending Conservative Euro-sceptics, angry at the
erosion of British parliamentary sovereignty to EC institutions.
The last-minute flurry over the speech was a vivid reminder of continuing
political sensitivity surrounding Europe as Mr John Major attempts to
reposition his government as enthusiastic to Europe before taking up the EC
presidency in July.
Next week, however, the government must face down a backbench rebellion in
the Commons, opposing the integration of last December's Maastricht treaty
on closer European union into British law. Tory opponents of the Maastricht
deal, which includes enhanced powers for the European Parliament, are due to
meet tonight to plan their strategy.
Last night, the anti-federalist Bruges Group said that while it believed no
royal trespassing into the political arena was intended, it was concerned at
any suggestion that parliamentary differences were unimportant.
Mr William Cash, a leading Conservative Euro-sceptic, said it was 'utterly
irresponsible' of whoever had written the draft to portray the Queen as
indifferent to the significance of Britain's parliamentary traditions.
Government officials had said the speech had been written by the Queen's
private staff in consultation with the Foreign Office.
By early evening, however, Buckingham Palace was disputing that
interpretation, underlining that it was drafted in close collaboration with
the Foreign Office and Downing Street and bore a similar status to a Queen's
Speech to parliament. Later, Downing Street attempted to play down the
controversy by insisting that the reference to 'national parliaments' had
been taken out of context. 'There is no suggestion of trivialising national
parliaments,' it said.
The government had hoped the Queen's speech would defuse the row between the
UK and its EC partners over London's refusal to lift all immigration
controls. Yesterday, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, warned Brussels
that the plan would provoke a growth in far right groups and threaten social
stability.
UK wins sympathy but little support on frontier checks, Page 2
Euro-sceptics, Page 12
Editorial comment, Page 18
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
