<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / International Company News: Hanson jibs at price of Krupp
crane subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HANSON, the Anglo-American conglomerate, has told Fried. Krupp, the German
steel and engineering group, that it is not willing to pay the Pounds 250m
(Dollars 442.5m) price tag for its loss-making crane business.
According to one of Hanson's financial advisers, negotiations collapsed at a
preliminary stage.
Krupp yesterday confirmed that it was in 'co-operation' talks with foreign
companies about the future of the business.
While the talks continued the group was also undertaking a sweeping internal
restructuring programme, a spokesman said. Mr Gerhard Cromme, chairman, said
last week that the mobile crane business was the only part of Krupp's plant
building division which failed to break even, and the market was expected to
continue its downward trend.
Similar negotiations and rationalisation measures are also under way with
the O&amp;K cranes division of Hoesch, which is currently being taken over by
Krupp.
Hanson is still expected to make its next big acquisition in the US,
although the group remains interested in expanding in continental Europe and
is looking at several possible opportunities.
Mr Derek Bonham, Hanson's newly appointed chief executive, believes that it
is important for Hanson to branch out of its traditional Anglo-American
markets but only at the right price.
Krupp's crane-making business was seen as a possible bolt-on acquisition to
Hanson Grove Industries, which boasts the largest hydraulic crane
manufacturer in the world.
Grove, which was spun off from Kidde after it was acquired by Hanson in 1987
for Pounds 1.75bn, made Dollars 85m operating profits on sales of Dollars
480m for the year to end-September 1991.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-8698</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CELA7ADEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920512
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Elswick edges ahead to Pounds 2.25m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELSWICK, which is focusing on print and packaging after divesting from
bicycles, slightly improved pre-tax profit last year, but was unable to pay
a final dividend because of below-the-line losses.
The pre-tax figure went up to Pounds 2.25m (Pounds 2.22m) on sales of Pounds
59.9m (Pounds 58.2m) in the year to January 31. A small decline in operating
profit to Pounds 3.29m (Pounds 3.4m) was offset by reduced interest payments
of Pounds 1.03m (Pounds 1.17m).
In December the group sold Falcon Cycles, ending more than 100 years of
involvement in the bicycle industry. Operating losses as well as the deficit
on the disposal were included in extraordinary charges. The Pounds 3.66m
total also took in the cost of closing a US domestic lawnmower business.
After a Pounds 2.15m drain on reserves, the group was left with a deficit on
its profit and loss account, preventing a final dividend from being paid.
Mr Bill Cross, chairman, said this was a 'technical glitch'. The share
premium account would be used to eliminate the deficit and dividend payments
should resume with this year's interim.
The core print and packaging division, involving self-adhesive labels,
garment labels and foil, made an operating profit of Pounds 2.64m (Pounds
2.61m) on sales of Pounds 26m (Pounds 24.3m). Mr David Cross, chief
executive and son of the chairman, said about Pounds 16.5m had been spent
between 1987 and 1990 on acquisitions to establish the division. Capital
spending amounted to more than Pounds 13m in the past five years and a
further Pounds 2.8m was scheduled for this year.
The equipment and services division saw profit fall to Pounds 644,000
(Pounds 1.01m) on sales of Pounds 23.6m (Pounds 23.9m). The benefits of
cost-cutting and reorganisation should begin to flow through next year, he
said. The businesses were being run as 'cash cows' and would eventually be
sold.
Bank borrowings fell from Pounds 4.96m to Pounds 518,000 with the help of
the disposal and cuts in working capital. However, counting about Pounds
4.5m of loan notes, year-end gearing stood at 77 per cent on shareholders'
funds of Pounds 6.54m (Pounds 8.8m).
Diluted earnings per share fell to 0.98p (1.02p). Omission of the final
dividend leaves shareholders with just 0.22p (0.6p) for the year.
COMMENT
While there might be some investor annoyance at the failure to pay a final
dividend, welcome by-products are a Pounds 1m saving and a lower base from
which to rebuild cover. Last year should also have been a low point for
pre-tax profit, with benefits to come from the expansion of print and
packaging, margin improvement in equipment and services and lower interest
costs. A rising tax charge should be the only drag on earnings. The
turnround story has been rather drawn out since the present management came
to the rescue in 1985. With bicycles no longer putting a spoke in the wheel,
the ultimate proof of the strategy will be the delivery of significant
profit increases from print and packaging. A forecast pre-tax profit of
Pounds 2.8m gives a prospective p/e of nearly 11 on yesterday's close of 10
1/2 p, not expensive for the sector.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
