FT  12 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Aberdeen Trust up by 77% to Pounds 1.04m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN TRUST, the fund management company, yesterday reported pre-tax
profits up 77 per cent, from Pounds 584,000 to Pounds 1.04m, for the half
year to March 31.
The improvement, however, reflected the elimination of exceptional costs.
Operating profits dipped from Pounds 1.21m to Pounds 1.04m.
Earnings per share were 0.97p (0.75p); the interim dividend is unchanged at
1p.
Mr George Robb, chairman, said that Cheval Investment Management, which
manages fixed interest funds for clients of Lloyd's of London, increased
funds under management by Pounds 75m to Pounds 400m as Lloyd's acquired new
clients.
Funds under group management were Pounds 1.1bn at the period end, compared
with Pounds 775m on September 30 1991.
Unlike most Scottish fund management groups which prefer to centralise their
fund management function, Aberdeen yesterday opened an office in Singapore
to manage funds in south-east Asian companies and assist marketing to
clients in the region.
