<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It would be a rare year that produced another drama serial as good as Anglo
Saxon Attitudes, and since the relationships within this splendid Angus
Wilson story are pretty tangled it is advisable to watch carefully from the
beginning (8.30 ITV). Such dedication will be rewarded. This excellent
adaptation by Andrew Davies works on all levels: among the backbiting
historians, the homosexual demi-monde of 1950s London, and above all in
telling the odd, and yet in so many ways recognisable, story of the
Middleton family. Richard Johnson gives the best performance I have seen
from him as the upstanding yet imperfect patriarch around whom so much
revolves.
In Assignment the estimable Michael Charlton returns to his native Australia
to investigate the national identity crisis (if that is what it is)
exemplified by Prime Minister Paul Keating's notorious comments about
Australia and Britain (7.45 BBC2). BBC1's drama Boys From The Bush, which
returns for a second series, is also set in Australia where some pretty
far-fetched and/or farcical stories are built around a tin-pot detective
agency (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
