   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY TRAVEL agents are 'incompetent and lazy' and waste money by making
basic errors and giving sloppy advice, according to a report from Which?,
the Consumers' Association magazine, published today.
The magazine says more than half its inquiries at 253 travel agents in 10
cities were handled badly, with agents telling half-truths and quoting
unnecessarily high fares.
Only one in five agents was able to find the cheapest routine flight to Nice
 -a Pounds 129 special offer from British Airways. A branch of AT Mays in
Manchester assured a researcher that a Pounds 244 Air France flight was the
cheapest available; the eight Lunn Poly branches in Glasgow quoted five
different fares.
Three out of five agents were unable to give satisfactory information about
holidays in Mykonos and two out of five provided less than useful advice
about Majorca, one of the most popular holiday destinations.
Which? says, however, that some agents performed with great competence and
spent much time finding the best deals. It says Hogg Robinson provided the
best service of the five big travel chains. Mays.
