FT  12 MAY 92 / Better scrutiny of Scots law is urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT should enable specifically Scottish legislation to be given
better and more detailed consideration, according to the journal of the Law
Society of Scotland, which represents Scotland's 8,000 solicitors.
The society says the government should 'give power to some body' for the
better consideration of Scottish legislation. This body could be a Scottish
parliament, an assembly, the Commons committee on Scottish affairs or the
Scottish grand committee, which is the committee of all Scottish MPs. The
society believes most Scottish lawyers would object to the creation of an
extra tier of government in Scotland and to the issuing of more Scottish
legislation.
The Edinburgh-based society, a statutory body, has not taken part in the
constitutional debate since the late 1970s.
The government is likely to examine the option of giving more power to the
Commons committee, which was not formed in the last parliament, and to
strengthening the Scottish grand committee, which meets occasionally in
Edinburgh as well as London. There has been speculation that it might create
some forum without tax-raising powers.
