<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / CBI optimistic over recovery prospects for small companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE most optimistic assessment of prospects for smaller companies for two
years emerges from the latest survey of industrial trends published by the
Confederation of British Industry today.
The quarterly industrial trends survey for smaller manufacturing companies
showed that though large companies are expected to continue to shed many
jobs over the next four months, smaller businesses employing fewer than 200
people each will make only a small reduction in employee numbers.
Small companies as well as large have cut jobs recently. But over the next
four months the number of small companies cutting employment is likely to be
almost balanced by those taking on more people, the CBI said.
The survey of small businesses found that:
Twenty-eight per cent said they were more optimistic about the general
business situation, while 18 per cent were less optimistic.
On balance, 10 per cent more businesses expected new orders to increase over
the next four months.
A positive balance of 10 per cent expected an increase in volume output over
the next four months, compared with 13 per cent which had recorded a decline
in the previous four months.
Cost pressures were at their weakest since the smaller companies report was
started in 1980.
Export orders declined in the preceding four months at a slightly faster
rate than experienced by larger manufacturers but they are expected to
increase again over the coming four months.
CBI, Publications Sales, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford Street, London WC1A
1DU. Pounds 10 to non-members.
</TEXT>
