FT  11 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: UK telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Last week's announcement that the National Grid is applying for a licence to
supply telephone services will not have worried BT or Mercury unduly. Groups
such as the electricity and water companies and British Rail were always
likely to take advantage of their national infrastructures and special
privileges. By law, they can no longer keep those privileges to themselves.
But their main problem will be to find the huge sums required if they are to
compete. In the year to last March, BT invested Pounds 2.4bn. In its last
financial year, Mercury invested Pounds 500m. It is hard to envisage the
National Grid playing in that league for years to come.
