<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / ITN chief seeks speedy reshaping of ownership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BOB PHILLIS, chief exec-utive of Independent Television News, has begun
the restructuring of his organisation and hopes to sign up the first new
shareholder before the end of this year.
The government decided that in future 51 per cent of ITN, at present a
wholly owned subsidiary of the ITV companies, should be held by non-ITV
companies. The end of 1994 has been set as the deadline for completing that
process.
Mr Phillis is keen to move much more quickly to remove uncertainty and also
because several ITV companies are interested in selling their stakes. Thames
Television, which lost its franchise, is expected to reduce its 22 per cent
stake in ITN to 20 per cent, but two other losers - TVS with 8 per cent and
Television South West with 2 per cent  - are expected to sell. Some of the
smaller ITV companies may also decide to follow. The tiny Channel TV, for
example, owns only 0.2 per cent of ITN.
London Weekend Television, in spite of retaining its franchise, is believed
to be interested in selling its ITN stake.
Mr Phillis has been talking to US television companies such as ABC, CBS and
Mr Ted Turner's CNN, and the first outside buyer might come from the US
industry. The purchase of a 20 per cent stake by a US broadcaster would also
help to put a value on an organisation that has been making the painful
transition from cost centre to profit centre.
Mr Michael Green's Carlton Television, which ousted Thames for the London
weekday franchise, has also written to ITN expressing interest in acquiring
a stake.
The restructuring is likely to involve a mixture of putting together willing
buyers and sellers, and raising capital.
If a workable structure emerges in which ITV companies still have a
majority, only then is Mr Phillis likely to ask Mr David Mellor, the
national heritage secretary, to consider removing the 51 per cent outside
shareholder rule.
</TEXT>
