<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / Shake-up planned for laws on secrecy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A REVIEW of secrecy laws, which might eventually open to public scrutiny
inspectors' reports on health and safety, drug and other companies, will be
set today as the next extension of the government's Citizen's Charter
programme.
Mr William Waldegrave, the cabinet minister responsible for seeing the
charter into action, will tell MPs that he sees a greater openness by
officials as an essential part of moves towards reducing central
government's role.
In accordance with the Tory election manifesto, he wants slimmer Whitehall
departments acting as policymakers and representing consumers, with other
government operations transferred increasingly to executive agencies.
Greater access to information would increase the power of consumers, he will
say in the Commons debate on last week's Queen's Speech.
An interdepartmental committee, chaired by Mr Andrew Wettnall, a senior
civil servant from the Cabinet Office, has been set up to trawl government
departments for areas where secrecy restrictions can be lifted. Mr
Waldegrave hopes legislation will be introduced next year.
However, ministers have disappointed consumer groups and opposition
politicians by ruling out a Freedom of Information Bill. Ministers argue
that such a bill would not guarantee that existing restrictions were lifted.
No decisions have been taken about what secrecy laws may be repealed but Mr
Waldegrave is believed to have told officials that he wants to consider all
sources of information received by the government to see whether more could
be released. That could include reports of health and safety inspectors and
possibly even by company inspectors.
Speaking yesterday on BBC Radio, Mr Waldegrave said he wanted to 'root out'
the 'Yes, Minister' culture of Whitehall, where it was assumed that members
of the public were unable to interpret information correctly.
'The answer from the bureaucracy is always, 'Don't give them the
information, they will misinterpret it',' he said. 'That must be the wrong
way around. Give out the information - and then explain what it means.'
</TEXT>
