<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / Fowler pledges big review of Tory machine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR NORMAN FOWLER, who takes over as Conservative party chairman today,
yesterday promised a 'fundamental review of the party's organisation and
structure'.
'We need to make sure that we are as efficient and effective as possible,'
he explained. 'My aim is to make this party the best political organisation
in Europe.'
He indicated that he might look favourably at increasing democracy in the
Conservative machine. There is pressure in the party for elections for
senior posts - including Sir Norman's - at Central Office. At present,
holders of such posts are chosen by the prime minister. Sir Norman also
indicated that he might publish fuller party accounts. The Sutton Coldfield
MP's responsibilities will include depleted party finances, boosting the
chances for women to become candidates in Commons and council elections, and
preparing for the 1994 elections to the European parliament.
Central Office is an unwieldy and costly machine that Sir Norman sees as
ripe for change. The general election campaign was lacklustre, even if the
result was a Tory win. Sir Norman, as the prime minister's 'minder' during
the campaign, saw at first hand the lack of cohesion - and Mr Major's
frustration. Unlike many previous party chairmen, Sir Norman will not join
the cabinet. He could have insisted on a cabinet post in the new government,
but says the extra responsibility would have stopped him getting out into
the country.
There will be staff cuts and changes at Central Office under his leadership.
He wants organisation to be improved in marginal seats and the central party
machine to be geared to giving the service expected by local activists.
The party is in the red. Central Office insiders say the election was
financed by a flurry of donations during the campaign and that the deficit
has not grown. The party's advertising budget for the general election,
believed to have been about Pounds 4.5m, was no more than half the amount
spent in the 1987 campaign. Sir Norman, a Tory knight of middle England,
will have to guard against defeats in by-elections. There were some
spectacular ones in the last parliament, such as the one at Eastbourne in
October 1990. With the government's majority now cut to 21, losses in this
parliament will be more costly.
When a member of Mrs Margaret Thatcher's government, Sir Norman acquired a
reputation for fighting Westminster battles with verve while shielding his
back.
He was loyal to Mrs Thatcher and successfully avoided much of the
controversy in his six years as social services secretary that plagued his
successors. Only subsequently was the department split into social security
and health. Under Mr John Major he helped to quell Tory backbenchers'
threats to the Maastricht Treaty by standing, successfully, for the post of
chairman of the party's backbench Europe committee.
In January 1990 Sir Norman, an Essex-born grammar school boy, resigned as
Mrs Thatcher's employment secretary, saying he wanted to spend more time
with his family. Now aged 54, he wants to return to the political fray.
Sir Norman explained that his children were older. 'I have almost to make
appointments with them', he added.
MR JOHN MAJOR has appointed three backbenchers to senior posts in the
Conservative party. Mr Gerry Malone, who won Winchester in the general
election, is to be a deputy chairman. Mr Tim Smith, MP for Beaconsfield, is
to be party vice-chairman in charge of finances and fund-raising. Mr Andrew
Mitchell, MP for Gedling, will be vice-chairman responsible for candidate
selection.
</TEXT>
