FT  11 MAY 92 / Telephone union says it is branching out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Communications Union is making progress in extending its
membership beyond BT and the Post Office and has won a foothold in the cable
TV industry and at Butlin's, the leisure company, according to a union
recruitment circular.
If UK union membership as a proportion of the working population is not to
dwindle to US levels, unions such as the NCU must expand out of their
shrinking, union-friendly heartlands and seek members in smaller companies
in communications and services. Mr Alan Harley, NCU national organiser, has
reported that the 150,000-strong union is on the way to surpassing its
modest target of recruiting 1,000 members outside BT and the Post Office by
the end of 1992.
The NCU has recruited 350 members in Mercury, the main BT competitor, after
visiting only 10 out of the 70 main sites, but the three-year aim of
recruiting up to half Mercury's 7,000 eligible staff may be over-optimistic.
</TEXT>
