<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / Gould seeks new leader-poll rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BRYAN GOULD, shadow environment secretary and contender for the party
leadership, has proposed a one member, one vote system for future leadership
contests that would end the block vote by unions and MPs.
In an attempt to cast himself as the most radical candidate and to build
support among constituency parties, Mr Gould says in an article in today's
Morning Star that union members who pay the political levy should be able to
convert it to party membership.
That would allow the abolition of Labour's electoral college, which at
present is composed of blocks of votes from the unions, constituency parties
and MPs. 'Like any other democratic institution, there should be one
category of individual membership, and membership alone should carry voting
rights,' Mr Gould says. His support is strongest among the constituency
parties.
The parliamentary party would retain the right of nomination, though fewer
signatures would be required under Mr Gould's scheme. Beyond that, MPs would
have no more rights than constituency members. He argues, however, that
there should continue to be a role for affiliated organisations, including
the unions, during policy making at party conferences. The unions would also
continue to be represented on Labour's ruling national executive committee
and on other party bodies.
His proposals may be received positively in the camp of Mr John Smith,
front-runner in the leadership race. Mr Tony Blair, shadow employment
secretary and a supporter of Mr Smith, said on BBC television yesterday that
he favoured moving to a one member, one vote system in the Labour movement
'with trade union levy payers, who at present . . . pay money but gain very
little influence, being brought into the Labour party'.
Mr Blair said Labour shared 'a bond of values' with the unions which was
more important than the institutional links, but he wanted to 'recast it for
a modern age'.
Mr Gould, who proposes a 'committee of inquiry' into Labour's structures and
constitution, says in his article that 'the link with the trade unions
continues to provide a crucial input from the real world of work into
Labour's deliberations'.
</TEXT>
